{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01QhqLSdY6Ngqvy6YcDy3yr3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The DC operating point shows Vout = 0.9V — the Lfb + Rdc approach sets the DC point correctly. But all AC measurements failed, meaning the gain is either 0 or the simulation didn't produce AC results.\n\nThe issue might be with my AC testbench setup. Let me reconsider:\n\n1. Lfb = 1GH from vout to vinn — this passes DC (short circuit at DC) but blocks AC (high impedance at AC). So at DC, vinn = vout, and the OTA is in unity-gain feedback for the DC operating point.\n\n\n2. Rdc = 0 ohm from vinn to cm shorts vinn to ground, which conflicts with Lfb connecting vinn to vout at DC. At AC, the inductor becomes open while the resistor still shorts vinn to ground, completely disconnecting the feedback path and breaking the circuit.\n\nAt AC, vinn is forced to ground potential while vinp sees the full 1V signal, so the OTA should show open-loop gain — but the measurements aren't working. I suspect the issue is that ngspice doesn't accept zero-ohm resistors, so I need to replace that with a very small resistance instead.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":448,"cache_read_input_tokens":228778,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":448},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"72d68435-d416-4390-89f1-41ec4e430727"}
