{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_017QG773NQvSA8wvCtLitcnU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have much better data. Key observations:\n\n**Vbn sweep (Vbp=0.83, Vbcp=0.85):**\n- Vbn=0.58: M11=456nA, M9=201nA, Vout=0.914V ← Good!\n\n**Vbp sweep (Vbn=0.58, Vbcp=0.85):**\n- Vbp=0.82: Vout=0.934V, M4_Vds=0.048V (triode), M6_Vds=0.817V ← Vout close to 0.9V\n\n\n- Vbp=0.84: Vout=0.557V, M4_Vds=0.060V, M6_Vds=1.182V\n\nThe output drops sharply between Vbp=0.82 and 0.84 as M4 transitions out of triode operation. Now I'm sweeping Vbcp to see how the cascode bias affects the overall behavior. Looking at the voltage relationships, I see that achieving Vout≈0.9V requires Vbp≈0.82V, but this pushes M4 into the triode region with insufficient headroom—there's a fundamental tradeoff between output voltage and device saturation that I need to resolve.\n\nThe real fix is to increase the current capability of M3 and M4 so they can supply the necessary current while maintaining saturation; with the current sizing, M3 is operating in subthreshold with a very small Vdsat of only ~0.062V, which severely limits the available voltage margin at the output node.\n\nLet me trace through the voltage constraints more carefully: at Vout=0.9V, M6 needs at least 0.06V across it to stay saturated, which means mid_n must be at least 0.96V, leaving 0.84V for M4—plenty of headroom in theory. But the simulation shows M4 with only 0.048V at Vout=0.934V, so something's off with my calculation.\n\nLooking at the actual simulation data: M4's Vds of 0.048V means mid_n sits at 1.752V, and M6's Vds of 0.817V confirms Vout at 0.935V. The issue is that M4 is barely conducting with such a small drain-source voltage, yet with Vsg=0.98V and |Vth| presumably around 0.4-0.5V, it should have plenty of overdrive to push current through.\n\nThe real problem is that M4 is operating in the linear region of subthreshold conduction where Vds is too small (48mV) to maintain the exponential current relationship—it's not acting as a proper current source anymore. To fix this, I need to either increase the gate bias to push M4 deeper into moderate inversion, or adjust the circuit topology so M4 has more headroom to develop a proper Vds.\n\nBut looking at the sweep data, when Vbp=0.855V and Vbcp=0.60V, M4 gets 265mV of Vds—excellent saturation—and the output naturally settles around 0.5V. So maybe the issue is that I'm trying to force Vout to 0.9V when the circuit architecture actually wants to operate at 0.5V. The input common-mode is specified at 0.9V, but that might not be compatible with where this topology naturally equilibrates.\n\nIf I tried lowering Vcm to 0.5V to match the natural output point, the input pair wouldn't have enough overdrive—M1 and M2 need Vcm above roughly 0.57V just to stay in saturation. So that won't work either. Let me try widening M3 and M4 instead to shift the operating point.\n\nMaking M3/M4 wider would increase their current capability and lower their output impedance, but in subthreshold operation the saturation voltage barely changes with width—it's still around 40mV regardless. The real constraint is that subthreshold devices have inherently poor gain and limited headroom, so I'm hitting a fundamental limit with this topology. needs at least 3-4 Vt ≈ 80-100mV of Vds to be in \"saturation\" (flat portion of Id-Vds curve). With only 48mV, it's on the slope.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The PMOS Vth in this model is ~1V, which means to get it into strong inversion (Vov > 150mV), we need |Vsg| > 1.15V. With VDD=1.8V, that leaves only 0.65V for everything else (M5/M6 cascode + output swing).\n\nFor a 1.8V supply with PFET |Vth|=1.0V, the practical approach is operating M3/M4 in subthreshold while ensuring Vds stays above 100mV for reliable saturation. This gives me a voltage budget where the maximum output swing reaches about 1.6V and the minimum is constrained by the cascoded NMOS saturation voltages at roughly 0.2V.\n\nThe core issue is that at Vbp=0.82V, M4 only has 48mV of Vds, which puts it on the linear region slope rather than saturation. To fix this, I need to increase Vbp to reduce M6's source-drain voltage, which is currently at 0.817V and pushing the intermediate node too high. Increasing Vbcp toward VDD would reduce M6's gate-source voltage and make it conduct less aggressively, but there's a tradeoff to consider.\n\nLooking at the Vbcp sweep data at Vbp=0.855V, when Vbcp=0.60V I get M4_Vds=0.265V with Vout=0.52V—the headroom is better but the output voltage is too low. The fundamental tension is that raising Vout requires more PMOS current, but more current pushes the intermediate node higher and squeezes M4's headroom. The cascode configuration is meant to boost impedance, but if I set Vbcp too close to Vbp to minimize the cascode's Vsd, I lose that impedance benefit. I'm exploring whether there's a way to reduce the PMOS cascode voltage drop without sacrificing the impedance gain.\n\nLet me try shifting the common-mode input voltage down to 0.5V so the output naturally settles at a better operating point with more headroom across all devices. But first I need to verify the input pair can function at that lower common-mode. Actually, I'm reconsidering the whole topology—what if I use a PMOS input pair instead of NMOS? With PMOS inputs, the threshold voltage works in my favor, and I can check whether the gate-source voltage requirements are satisfied at a lower common-mode like 0.9V.\n\nHmm, that's not working either—the PMOS input still runs into the same threshold voltage constraint. Let me be pragmatic here: I'll accept that the PFET operates in subthreshold, set the bias voltage to push the output close to 0.9V even if M4 ends up in triode, and then verify the AC gain is still acceptable. Looking at my simulation data from Vbp=0.82 and Vbcp=0.85, I got around 31dB of gain, so let me explore what happens if I adjust Vbcp to 0.65 while keeping Vbp at 0.82—the output should stay near 0.93V, and I can check how M4's drain-source voltage changes.\n\nActually, I need to be careful about which bias point I'm referencing; I think I used Vbp=0.855 in that sweep, not 0.82. Rather than chase down the exact numbers, let me just run the AC simulation directly at these new bias points and see what gain I actually get—I suspect lowering Vbcp will improve things.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2361,"cache_read_input_tokens":235245,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2361},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"74dbc312-955e-470c-8cac-c125d934c8fb"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_017QG773NQvSA8wvCtLitcnU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01VRBRb6AvfQoaPPZDwPhMyk","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"# Quick AC check at a better bias point\n# Vbp=0.82 (Vout≈0.93 in feedback), Vbcp=0.65 (more headroom for M4)\ncat > /tmp/quick_ac.spice << 'EOF'\n.lib \"sky130_minimal.lib.spice\" tt\n.include \"ota_foldcasc.spice\"\n\nVdd vdd 0 dc 1.8\nVss vss 0 dc 0\n\nVbn  vbn  0 dc 0.58\nVbcn vbcn 0 dc 0.80\nVbp  vbp  0 dc 0.82\nVbcp vbcp 0 dc 0.65\n\nVcm cm 0 dc 0.9\nVac vinp cm dc 0 ac 1\n\nLfb vout fb 1G\nRfb fb vinn 1\nRbias vinn cm 1G\n\nXota vinp vinn vout vdd vss vbn vbcn vbp vbcp ota_foldcasc\nCL vout 0 10p\n\n.ac dec 100 1 100Meg\n\n.control\n  run\n  meas ac gain_db MAX vdb(vout)\n  meas ac ugb WHEN vdb(vout)=0 FALL=1\n  meas ac phase_at_ugb FIND vp(vout) AT=ugb\n  let pm = phase_at_ugb + 180\n  echo \"Gain(dB): $&gain_db\"\n  echo \"UGB(Hz): $&ugb\"\n  echo \"PM(deg): $&pm\"\n  quit\n.endc\n.end\nEOF\ncp /tmp/quick_ac.spice . && /usr/bin/ngspice -b quick_ac.spice 2>&1 | grep -E \"(Gain|UGB|PM|gain_db|ugb|phase)\" | grep -v \"Warning\" | head -10","description":"Quick AC test at better bias","timeout":120000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2361,"cache_read_input_tokens":235245,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2361},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"f1959ce7-d7d9-4853-b327-e8172570b483"}
