)                         \nIndex   frequency       v(vout)                         \nIndex   frequency       v(vout)                         \nIndex   frequency       v(vout)                         \n@m.xota.m4[vds] = 2.251804e-01\n@m.xota.m4[vdsat] = 5.641667e-02\n@m.xota.m4[id] = 3.174299e-07\n@m.xota.m6[vds] = 1.057028e+00","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0147kSkCUQKeQ9p9f7NNCi9K","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The gain is NEGATIVE (-33 dB). This means the AC output is actually attenuated, not amplified. The OTA is not working as an amplifier in this configuration.\n\nThe issue: the gain is negative because the output is INVERTING from the AC perspective. But that's expected since we're measuring Vout with AC on Vinp. Let me check — actually, gain_db = MAX(vdb(vout)) = -33 means the maximum gain over all frequencies is -33 dB, which means the output is always less than the input. This is strange.\n\nWait, I think the problem is the testbench setup. \n\nWith the Lfb-Rfb-Rbias configuration, the DC feedback forces vout to track Vinp at 0.9V, but at AC frequencies, the large feedback inductor acts as an open circuit. This leaves vinn essentially floating through the massive 1G ohm bias resistor, which means the AC signal path isn't properly set up. The 1 ohm feedback resistor can't overcome the impedance mismatch, so the amplifier isn't actually amplifying the input signal. connects fb to vinn  \n- Rbias = 1G → connects vinn to cm (AC ground)\n\nAt AC, vinn is connected through Rfb (1 ohm) to fb, and fb is connected through Lfb (open at AC) to vout. So vinn → Rfb → fb (floating at AC). Then vinn → Rbias → cm (ground).\n\nSo vinn has two paths: through Rfb to floating node fb, and through Rbias (1G) to ground. Since Rfb << Rbias, vinn ≈ fb (the floating node). \n\nBut fb is connected to vout through Lfb (high Z at AC). So the AC signal at vout doesn't reach fb or vinn. Good.\n\nvinn at AC: connected to cm through 1G ohm. This is essentially floating at AC — 1G ohm at audio frequencies with the gate capacitance creating a pole around 1 MHz, so at low frequencies vinn is effectively grounded.\n\nThe -33 dB gain suggests the OTA might not be set up correctly, or there's an issue with the DC operating point. Let me check the actual output voltage and try plotting the gain directly to see what's happening. The problem could be that the output is being attenuated rather than amplified, which might indicate an inverting configuration or a biasing issue I'm missing. wrong3. There's a grounding issue\n\nLet me reconsider the gain polarity. In a folded cascode:- Increase Vinp → M1 Id increases → fold_p drops → BUT fold_p is not the output\n- M1 increases → M2 decreases (tail shared) → at output: M6 delivers more than M8+M2 sinks → vout rises- So the gain from vinp to vout is POSITIVE\n\nBut wait — in my circuit, M2 drain = vout. So:- Increase Vinp → M1 Id increases → M2 Id decreases (tail shared)\n- M2 drain = vout. Less M2 current means less current pulling vout down.\n- But M4/M6 deliver constant current (set by Vbp). So excess current charges CL → vout rises.\n\nSo gain is positive from vinp to vout. A positive gain should show positive gain_db in the AC measurement, but I'm getting -33 dB instead. Let me check if the phase is 180° at DC—that would suggest the transfer function is actually inverting. The fact that the maximum vdb(vout) caps out at -33 dB is suspicious, so I need to examine the raw AC data to understand what's happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3748,"cache_read_input_tokens":244650,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3748},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"e05fb7c4-3488-46d3-abc3-9335b8264a09"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0147kSkCUQKeQ9p9f7NNCi9K","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KDbT9nE8h38tNmaY4W4CA9","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat > quick_ac2.spice << 'EOF'\n.lib \"sky130_minimal.lib.spice\" tt\n.include \"ota_foldcasc.spice\"\n\nVdd vdd 0 dc 1.8\nVss vss 0 dc 0\n\nVbn  vbn  0 dc 0.58\nVbcn vbcn 0 dc 0.80\nVbp  vbp  0 dc 0.855\nVbcp vbcp 0 dc 0.65\n\nVcm cm 0 dc 0.9\nVac vinp cm dc 0 ac 1\n\n* Simple approach: connect vinn to vcm for DC bias, open-loop\nVinn_bias vinn cm dc 0\n\nXota vinp vinn vout vdd vss vbn vbcn vbp vbcp ota_foldcasc\nCL vout 0 10p\n\n.ac dec 100 1 100Meg\n\n.control\n  run\n  * Check gain at a few frequencies\n  meas ac gain_1hz FIND vdb(vout) AT=1\n  meas ac gain_1k  FIND vdb(vout) AT=1000\n  meas ac gain_10k FIND vdb(vout) AT=10000\n  meas ac phase_1hz FIND vp(vout) AT=1\n  echo \"Gain at 1Hz: $&gain_1hz dB, phase: $&phase_1hz deg\"\n  echo \"Gain at 1kHz: $&gain_1k dB\"\n  echo \"Gain at 10kHz: $&gain_10k dB\"\n\n  meas ac gain_db MAX vdb(vout)\n  meas ac ugb WHEN vdb(vout)=0 FALL=1\n  quit\n.endc\n.end\nEOF\n/usr/bin/ngspice -b quick_ac2.spice 2>&1 | grep -E \"(Gain|gain_|phase_|ugb)\" | grep -v \"Warning\" | head -15","description":"AC test open-loop (no feedback)","timeout":120000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3748,"cache_read_input_tokens":244650,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3748},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"0701c3ec-8027-4681-aa4b-9127c4360d9e"}
