{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011UbWTGs7pm9o2fm652R5uR","type":"tool_result","content":"Circuit: * ============================================================\n======================================================\n======================================================\nGain at 0.1Hz: -59.4285 dB\nGain at 1Hz: -59.4339 dB\nGain at 10Hz: -60.0059 dB\nGain at 100Hz: -35.6268 dB\nGain at 1kHz: -44.8551 dB\nGain at 10kHz: -45.6856 dB\nGain at 100kHz: -45.7438 dB\nPhase at 1Hz: 0.000327988 deg\nPhase at 1kHz: -0.0435029 deg\nPhase at 100kHz: -0.0387313 deg\nMAX Gain: -16.7093 dB\nUGB:  Hz\nPhase at UGB:  deg\n======================================================","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"acab4ef2-a65c-4271-9e8a-8710e6dbb381","timestamp":"2026-03-22T22:45:16.419Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Circuit: * ============================================================\n======================================================\n======================================================\nGain at 0.1Hz: -59.4285 dB\nGain at 1Hz: -59.4339 dB\nGain at 10Hz: -60.0059 dB\nGain at 100Hz: -35.6268 dB\nGain at 1kHz: -44.8551 dB\nGain at 10kHz: -45.6856 dB\nGain at 100kHz: -45.7438 dB\nPhase at 1Hz: 0.000327988 deg\nPhase at 1kHz: -0.0435029 deg\nPhase at 100kHz: -0.0387313 deg\nMAX Gain: -16.7093 dB\nUGB:  Hz\nPhase at UGB:  deg\n======================================================","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01XQ9mWkPuyGmHyqZv8aC4xm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Gain is negative across ALL frequencies! This confirms the OTA is not amplifying. The phase is near 0 degrees everywhere, meaning the output is just attenuated, not inverted.\n\nThe most likely explanation: the open-loop DC operating point has all devices in triode (Vout ≈ 0.05V or 1.76V), and the inductor feedback doesn't effectively set the operating point because the inductor reactance at very low frequencies isn't zero — it's j*2*pi*f*1G which at 0.1 Hz = j*628M ohm. This is a high impedance even at 0.1 Hz, so the feedback isn't actually working.\n\n\nThe 1GH inductor at 0.1 Hz has impedance of 628 Mohm, which is comparable to the OTA's output impedance, so the inductor isn't acting as a short circuit at the lowest frequencies and the DC feedback loop is broken. I need to either use a much larger inductor, start the AC sweep at a much lower frequency, or reconsider the approach entirely.\n\nActually, looking back at the unity-gain feedback test with Rfb=1ohm, I got a gain of 30.94 dB at 63 Hz with a unity-gain bandwidth of 29.7 kHz—that was actually working, just with lower gain than expected. The key difference is that with Rfb=1ohm, the feedback is always active for both DC and AC, whereas the inductor approach only provides DC feedback, leaving the AC response vulnerable at low frequencies.\n\nBut wait, I'm confusing myself here. If the open-loop gain is around 35.5x (31 dB), then with unity-gain feedback the closed-loop gain should be roughly 35.5/(1+35.5) ≈ 0.97, which is -0.3 dB, not the 31 dB I measured. That measurement must have been capturing something different—maybe the AC source on vinp with Rfb creating a short between vout and vinn means the circuit isn't actually in closed-loop feedback the way I thought. The real issue is the operating point—the circuit isn't properly biased, so I need to redesign it to push all devices into saturation. I'll increase the current from the PMOS sources (M3/M4) relative to the NMOS bottom (M9/M10) by widening the top devices or adjusting the bias voltage, which should force the output to settle at a higher voltage where M4 has enough headroom.\n\nBut I'm running into a fundamental constraint: with VDD at 1.8V and the PMOS threshold around 1.0V, there's barely 0.8V left for the voltage drops across M3, M5, and the output swing, so even at 0.8V output, M4 will still be pushed into the triode region.\n\nLet me work through what's actually achievable. If M4's source is at VDD and its gate is Vbp, then for M4 to stay in saturation I need Vds_M4 above roughly 100mV, which caps mid_n around 1.7V. Similarly, with M6's source at mid_n and its drain at the output, saturation requires Vds_M6 above 100mV, so the output can't exceed about 1.7V either.\n\nOn the NMOS side, M10 and M8 form a similar stack—M10's drain (src_n8) needs to be above 0.1V for saturation, and M8's drain (the output) needs to be above 0.2V. This gives me an output swing from roughly 0.2V to 1.6V, with a midpoint around 0.9V that should be reachable. The real challenge is keeping M4 in saturation when the output sits at 0.9V.\n\nAt that operating point, M6 needs a source-drain voltage above 0.1V, which pushes mid_n above 1.0V, while M4 needs the same margin, capping mid_n below 1.7V. That's actually a reasonable window, but the previous design had mid_n at 1.76V—way too high because M6's gate-source voltage was oversized. Let me trace through what's driving that: with Vbcp at 0.85V and mid_n at 1.76V, M6's Vsg becomes quite large, which is pulling the bias point too high.\n\nNow I'm looking at the equilibrium condition—mid_n settles where the current through M4 equals the current through M6, since they're stacked in series. The voltage divides between them based on their individual current-voltage characteristics, so I need to examine how M4's gate-source and drain-source voltages affect its current output. Looking at the device dimensions and test data, M6 with W=8u and L=0.5u shows about 150nA at Vsg=0.9V, but I need 500nA to match M4's current. The test data suggests Vsg needs to be around 0.97V to hit that target, which means mid_n = Vbcp + 0.97. This creates a problem though—with Vbcp=0.85V, that gives mid_n=1.82V, which exceeds the 1.8V supply rail, so I need to reconsider the bias point with a lower Vbcp value.\n\nDropping Vbcp to 0.70V gives mid_n=1.67V, which keeps M4 in saturation with only 0.13V headroom. For the feedback loop to work, M6 needs to pull vout down to 0.9V, requiring a 0.77V source-drain voltage—well into saturation, which is what I need for current matching.\n\nWhen I tested this same bias point earlier with Vbp=0.82V in unity-gain feedback, I got vout=0.976V with M4 at 0.155V (still saturated) and M6 at 0.669V. That configuration actually works, so I should re-run the AC analysis with these bias values using proper open-loop measurement to verify the gain and stability.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":365,"cache_read_input_tokens":257026,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":365},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"54e320f4-0b1b-4297-ba5e-476bbb0123ae"}
