{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0183KHdVBMTCouMXtEuXoZwz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Much better results now! But they're confusing:\n\n- At very low frequencies (0.1-1 Hz): Gain ≈ 0 dB (unity gain) — because the inductor is conducting (low impedance at low f), creating unity-gain feedback- At 100 Hz: Gain = 25.6 dB — the inductor starts opening up, revealing the open-loop gain\n- MAX Gain = 49.3 dB — this is likely the peak open-loop gain\n- UGB = 30 kHz — the unity-gain bandwidth- PM = 180-1.38 = 178.6° — very high phase margin\n\n\nThe 49.3 dB peak is where the inductor has opened up enough to expose the OTA's gain, but before its internal poles dominate the response. To find the true DC open-loop gain, I need to look at a frequency where the inductor is fully open (high impedance) yet still below the OTA's dominant pole frequency. At lower frequencies like 0.1 Hz, the inductor impedance drops to around 628M ohm, which is only about 6 times the OTA's output resistance, so the feedback isn't fully open and reduces the gain. This means the 25.6 dB reading at 100 Hz is probably closer to the true open-loop DC gain, and I need to find the actual peak to understand what's happening across the frequency range.\n\nLet me examine the full Bode plot data and also test with a much larger inductor value to push the crossover frequency down significantly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":360,"cache_read_input_tokens":260770,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":360},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"dc844f81-78b8-4e1f-b497-3bd7c2960252"}
