{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Hku78M4eA6A8f9DkcbS3yw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now we're getting somewhere! With the output forced to 0.9V:\n\nOutput resistance (from DC sweep) = 75.8 MOhm (negative sign is from the current direction convention). This is much higher than the 0.6 MOhm at the railed operating point.\n\nThe gds values at this operating point:\n- M2 gds = 2.4e-8 → ro_M2 = 41.7 MOhm\n- M4 gds = 9.87e-8 → ro_M4 = 10.1 MOhm\n- M6 gds = 6.45e-8 → ro_M6 = 15.5 MOhm, gm6 = 8.96 uA/V\n\n\n- M8 gds = 3.86e-8 → ro_M8 = 25.9 MOhm, gm8 = 5.16 uA/V\n- M10 gds = 3.23e-8 → ro_M10 = 31.0 MOhm\n\nAll devices are in saturation, confirming the operating point is valid. Now I need to work through the output resistance calculation for the PMOS cascode stage looking back from the output node.\n\nFor the PMOS side, I'm combining the transconductance gain with the parallel combination of the cascode transistor and current source output impedances, which gives me about 1.24 GOhm. The NMOS cascode branch yields a higher impedance of around 4.14 GOhm due to the larger transconductance and output resistances. Now I'm checking the impedance contribution from M2.\n\nThe impedance of M2 with source degeneration comes out to about 83 MOhm, and when I parallel all three impedance paths together, the total output resistance is dominated by M2's 83 MOhm, giving me roughly 76 MOhm—which matches the measured value of 75.8 MOhm almost perfectly. The cascoded branches are contributing their high impedances as intended. Now I need to calculate the overall voltage gain by multiplying the transconductance of the input stage by this output resistance.\n\nWith the transistor dimensions and bias current in subthreshold, I'm getting a transconductance around 6.1 µA/V, which would predict a gain of about 464 or 53 dB. But the actual measured gain was only 37.6 dB—about 76x—which is significantly lower. The issue seems to be that in the unity-gain feedback configuration, the differential input isn't actually zero; there's a 76 mV offset between the two inputs, meaning M1 and M2 are carrying different currents and the effective transconductance is reduced from what I calculated.\n\nLooking at the DC sweep data where the gain came out to 75.9, I can work backwards: if the output resistance is 75.8 MΩ from the forced-output measurement, then the transconductance at this operating point must be only about 1.0 µA/V—much lower than expected. This suggests the measurement setup itself might be affecting the result, particularly how the 1-ohm feedback resistor interacts with the circuit topology and creates an unexpected voltage divider effect. The discrepancy comes down to operating point: at the forced output where both inputs sit at 0.9V, the differential pair is perfectly balanced, but in the unity-gain feedback configuration there's a 31mV offset that throws the pair out of balance, causing M1 to carry less current and exhibit lower transconductance around 1.0 µA/V compared to the expected 5-6 µA/V at the balanced point.\n\nNow I need to recalculate the gain using the correct operating point—the 75.8 MΩ output resistance I measured was at the forced operating point, not at the actual unity-gain feedback operating point where Vout sits around 0.93V with the differential pair unbalanced, so I need to determine what Rout actually is at that configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1463,"cache_read_input_tokens":283314,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1463},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"fc4ac022-510d-4dea-97e5-9565abecba7a"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Hku78M4eA6A8f9DkcbS3yw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01BmpGrn1qJoAiMViipaLB5f","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat > gain_direct.spice << 'EOF'\n.lib \"sky130_minimal.lib.spice\" tt\n.include \"ota_foldcasc.spice\"\n\nVdd vdd 0 dc 1.8\nVss vss 0 dc 0\nMbn vbn vbn 0 0 sky130_fd_pr__nfet_01v8__model W=4u L=4u nf=1\nIbias vdd vbn dc 500n\nVbcn vbcn 0 dc 0.80\nMbp vbp vbp vdd vdd sky130_fd_pr__pfet_01v8__model W=8u L=1u nf=2\nIbp vbp 0 dc 500n\nVbcp vbcp 0 dc 0.70\n\n* Fix output at 0.9V, sweep diff input\nVinn vinn 0 dc 0.9\nVinp vinp 0 dc 0.9\n\nXota vinp vinn vout vdd vss vbn vbcn vbp vbcp ota_foldcasc\nVfix vout 0 dc 0.9\n\n* Tiny sweep of Vinp around 0.9V\n.dc Vinp 0.8999 0.9001 0.00001\n\n.control\n  run\n  meas dc i_low FIND i(Vfix) AT=0.8999\n  meas dc i_high FIND i(Vfix) AT=0.9001\n  * Transconductance: Gm = di/dVinp\n  let Gm = -(i_high - i_low) / 0.0002\n  echo \"Transconductance Gm = $&Gm A/V\"\n  \n  * Gain = Gm * Rout = Gm * 75.8M\n  let A = Gm * 75.8e6\n  let A_db = 20*log(abs(A))/log(10)\n  echo \"Open-loop gain = $&A = $&A_db dB\"\n  \n  * Also measure gm1 directly\n  op\n  echo \"gm1=$&@m.xota.m1[gm] gm2=$&@m.xota.m2[gm]\"\n  echo \"M1 Id=$&@m.xota.m1[id] M2 Id=$&@m.xota.m2[id]\"\n  quit\n.endc\n.end\nEOF\n/usr/bin/ngspice -b gain_direct.spice 2>&1 | grep -E \"^(Tran|Open|gm|M[12])\" | head -10","description":"Directly measure Gm and gain","timeout":60000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1463,"cache_read_input_tokens":283314,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1463},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"b9ca5600-5be8-4b56-96c8-7972bb6652eb"}
