{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01KpaWPa5oKVdFNgCQw9tDGs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still only 5 dB gain! The problem is the same: the 10T resistor doesn't provide adequate feedback to force the DC operating point. At DC, 10T ohm is essentially open, so no feedback. The output is railed (at 0.05V or 1.76V), and all devices are in triode.\n\nI keep running into the same issue: without proper DC feedback, the operating point rails. And with proper DC feedback (like the inductor or short-circuit), the AC measurement is distorted by the feedback.\n\nThe correct approach for this measurement is:1. \n\nI need to set up unity-gain feedback to establish the DC operating point, then break the loop at AC using a proper technique. The inductor approach with a very large L should work if I start the AC sweep at a sufficiently high frequency where the inductor impedance is effectively infinite. Let me try the inductor approach again but begin the AC sweep at 10 Hz instead—at that frequency, a 1T inductor has impedance around 6.28e13 ohm, which is essentially open circuit and won't interfere with the feedback break. Though I'm still running into issues with this approach.\n\nThe real solution is to use an even larger inductor like 1P (1e15 H), which gives very high impedance at low frequencies for AC analysis while maintaining a short at DC to set the operating point. Looking back at my earlier results with the 1T inductor, I'm seeing the feedback is active at 0.1 Hz (unity gain around -0.27 dB) but transitions to open-loop behavior by 100 Hz (25.6 dB), with the peak gain reaching 49-56 dB. The transition region around 100 Hz to 1 kHz shows the gain climbing from about 14 dB with a 1G inductor to 25 dB with a 1T inductor, which represents where the loop is actually breaking.\n\nWith the 1T inductor, the inductor becomes effectively open at frequencies well above 0.012 Hz (where its impedance matches the OTA output impedance), so the gain should flatten out from roughly 0.1 Hz up to the dominant pole. But my measurements show something odd—the gain was -9.6 dB at 1 Hz and jumped to 15 dB at 10 Hz with the 1T inductor, suggesting the transition is happening in that 1-10 Hz window rather than where I'd expect it, and by 100 Hz the gain settles around 14.4 dB in what should be the flat region.\n\nThe measured flat-region gain of 14.4 dB is nowhere near the expected 53 dB, which tells me the actual open-loop gain is significantly lower than my calculations predicted. I'm wondering if the inductor feedback is shifting the operating point in a way that changes the gain, so I should verify the bias conditions with the inductor in place. Alternatively, I could write a script to properly set the operating point, linearize the circuit, and compute the gain analytically to compare against simulation, or I could just accept that the peak gain I measured with the 1T inductor—around 56.2 dB at some intermediate frequency—might actually be the true open-loop gain, with the lower flat region being an artifact of how the inductor impedance interacts with the rest of the circuit.\n\nIf the peak represents the actual DC gain, then 56 dB is much closer to my 65 dB target. The inductor behavior would explain this: at DC it shorts out the feedback (unity gain), then as frequency rises the inductor impedance increases, allowing the open-loop gain to emerge and peak before rolling off at the OTA's dominant pole. To test this, I could measure the gain at 100 Hz across different inductor values to see if it converges, though my initial measurements show the gain actually decreased when I went from 1G to 1T at that frequency, which is puzzling.\n\nLooking more carefully at the data, the larger inductor shifted the peak to lower frequencies—the maximum gain increased from 49 dB to 56 dB, but at 100 Hz specifically the gain dropped from 25.6 dB to 14.4 dB because the circuit is now below the resonance peak at that frequency. So the inductor is opening at a lower frequency with the larger value, and the peak itself represents the resonance between the inductor and the output impedance.\n\nThe peak gain is climbing toward the true DC open-loop gain as the inductor gets larger, though 56 dB is already higher than my Gm×Rout estimate of 53 dB—that extra boost is likely from the resonance. Let me try a much larger inductor value to see if the peak settles, or better yet, use SPICE's `.tf` command to directly measure the DC transfer function with the inductor feedback in place, since the inductor acts as a short at DC and will give me the actual closed-loop DC gain.\n\nFrom the `.tf` measurement with L=1T, I'm getting a closed-loop gain of 37.6 dB, but this contradicts my Rout-based calculation of 53.5 dB. The issue is that the `.tf` is measuring at the actual operating point where the inductor feedback has created a 31 mV offset between the differential pair inputs, throwing M1 and M2 out of balance and reducing the effective transconductance.\n\nWith Vinp at 0.9V and Vinn at 0.931V, M2 is pulling more current than M1, which lowers the transconductance from Vinp to the output to around 5.0 µA/V instead of the nominal 6.2 µA/V. The output impedance also degrades at this unbalanced point since the device currents are mismatched, so the overall gain suffers. This explains why the measured gain is lower—the OTA's performance is genuinely degraded when operating with this offset.\n\nThe circuit could theoretically achieve 53 dB if perfectly balanced, but the inherent 31mV offset brings it down to around 38 dB in practice. Rather than chase the 65 dB target right now, I'll accept the current performance and move forward with testing the rest of the testbenches, then iterate on the sizing later if needed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2429,"cache_read_input_tokens":287516,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2429},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"f6397b76-98de-425f-b878-d4739a3805e0"}
