{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01WMEMCKtr6LdxhopqJc6cih","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The inoise_spectrum values at index 299-301 are around 1.96e-6 V/sqrt(Hz). But I need to know what frequency these correspond to. With dec 100 from 1 to 1Meg, the frequency at index 300 is:f = 1 * 10^(300/100) = 10^3 = 1000 Hz. ✓So inoise at 1kHz = 1.96e-6 V/sqrt(Hz) = 1960 nV/sqrt(Hz). That's WAY too high (target < 200 nV/sqrt(Hz)).Wait, this is the output-referred noise divided by the gain? No — `inoise_spectrum` should be the input-referred noise. Let me check.In ngspice, `.noise V(vout) Vac dec 100 1 1Meg`:- `onoise_spectrum` = output noise spectral density V/sqrt(Hz)\n\n\n- `inoise_spectrum` = input-referred noise = onoise / gain\n\nWith the inductor feedback, ngspice's noise analysis uses the transfer function from Vac to V(vout) as the gain. At 1kHz, the AC analysis showed a gain of about 23 dB or roughly 14x, so the input-referred noise would be onoise divided by 14, which gives me around 3 µV/sqrt(Hz).\n\nBut ngspice is actually reporting 1.96 µV/sqrt(Hz) at 1kHz, which already accounts for the feedback topology. The true input-referred noise of the bare OTA itself is much lower—around 15.6 nV/sqrt(Hz) when I divide the output noise by the open-loop gain of 2660. The key insight is that the feedback configuration changes what the input-referred noise measurement represents, so I need to be careful about whether I'm looking at the OTA's intrinsic noise or the noise as seen through the feedback network. ≈ 2.94 uV/sqrt(Hz), but ngspice is reporting 1.96e-6 instead—likely because the internal transfer function calculation differs from my manual AC measurement. Either way, 1.96 uV/sqrt(Hz) is well above the 200 nV target, and the inductor feedback might be skewing the noise analysis. Let me try a direct open-loop configuration with ideal voltage sources to force the DC operating point and get a cleaner measurement of the OTA's intrinsic noise.\n\nActually, I'm running into a fundamental issue: ngspice's noise analysis requires an AC source and a defined transfer function, but with the output forced to a fixed point, there's no gain and the input-referred noise becomes undefined. I'll note these results for now and come back to refining the noise measurement approach later—first let me check the other testbenches.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":266,"cache_read_input_tokens":325734,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":266},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"69028b2e-c4f0-4ccd-a7b5-0dbf74ec7c5d"}
