{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MiZd4mAhdPcfXzDpvd8a4y","type":"tool_result","content":"Circuit: * cmrr analysis - vibrosense ota\n======================================================\n  CMRR Analysis Results\n  CMRR(f) = A_diff(f) - A_cm(f)  [dB]\n======================================================\n  1 Hz:    -39.1795 dB\n  1 kHz:   -39.1852 dB\n  10 kHz:  -39.7068 dB\n  100 kHz: -47.2949 dB\n  1 MHz:   -51.3733 dB\nDC common-mode gain (1-10 Hz): -39.1795 dB\nNote: CMRR = diff_gain_dB - acm_dB\n======================================================","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"9248b0e4-8916-4483-99fb-f29e32613d0d","timestamp":"2026-03-22T23:05:34.329Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Circuit: * cmrr analysis - vibrosense ota\n======================================================\n  CMRR Analysis Results\n  CMRR(f) = A_diff(f) - A_cm(f)  [dB]\n======================================================\n  1 Hz:    -39.1795 dB\n  1 kHz:   -39.1852 dB\n  10 kHz:  -39.7068 dB\n  100 kHz: -47.2949 dB\n  1 MHz:   -51.3733 dB\nDC common-mode gain (1-10 Hz): -39.1795 dB\nNote: CMRR = diff_gain_dB - acm_dB\n======================================================","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_019g8NNM4anGYHgVuGHs1gWs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The PSRR and CMRR results show:\n\nPSRR: The VDD-to-output gain at 1kHz is about 2 dB. PSRR = diff_gain - vdd_gain. But the results show PSRR at 1kHz = 2 dB, which is very low (target is >50 dB).\n\nWait, I think the testbench is reporting the VDD-to-output gain directly, not the PSRR. The PSRR should be computed as:PSRR = DC_gain_dB - VDD_to_output_gain_dB\n\n\nIf the DC gain is 68 dB and the VDD-to-output gain at 1kHz is 2 dB, then PSRR = 68 - 2 = 66 dB. Looking at the testbench output more carefully, the formula shows \"PSRR(f) = A_diff(f) - Vout/Vdd(f)\", and the 2 dB value at 1kHz appears to be the VDD-to-output gain itself, not the computed PSRR.\n\nFor CMRR, the negative values like -39 dB at 1Hz represent the common-mode gain. Since CMRR is calculated as diff_gain minus CM_gain, that gives me 68 - (-39) = 107 dB, which would be excellent performance. The testbench is showing the CM gain directly rather than the final CMRR calculation.\n\nNow looking at PSRR more carefully: the VDD disturbance measurement shows 2 dB gain at 1kHz, but I need to use the differential gain at that same frequency from the AC sweep, which is around 23 dB from the inductor-feedback data. That means PSRR at 1kHz is actually 23 - 2 = 21 dB, much lower than the 66 dB I'd get if I incorrectly used the peak diff gain of 68 dB.\n\nThe real issue is that both the PSRR and CMRR testbenches are picking up the same inductor-feedback distortion effects as the AC analysis, so all these measurements are inherently limited by that artifact. I'll document this measurement limitation and move forward with compiling the full results, then run the corner analysis.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2002,"cache_read_input_tokens":326000,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2002},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01e4b3b1-6a11-48e6-b3e7-40758ef8985d","uuid":"4037ec14-fa99-4a89-9231-a6dd8a198916"}
